Read and explore data¶

  • 1 string column
  • 13 numeric columns
  • total of 14 columns
  • No NA values

Meaning of each column:

  • credit.policy: 1 if the customer meets the credit underwriting criteria of LendingClub.com, and 0 otherwise. purpose: The purpose of the loan (takes values "credit_card", "debt_consolidation", "educational", "major_purchase", "small_business", and "all_other").
  • int.rate: The interest rate of the loan, as a proportion (a rate of 11% would be stored as 0.11). Borrowers judged by LendingClub.com to be more risky are assigned higher interest rates.
  • installment: The monthly installments owed by the borrower if the loan is funded.
  • log.annual.inc: The natural log of the self-reported annual income of the borrower. dti: The debt-to-income ratio of the borrower (amount of debt divided by annual income).
  • fico: The FICO credit score of the borrower. days.with.cr.line: The number of days the borrower has had a credit line.
  • revol.bal: The borrower's revolving balance (amount unpaid at the end of the credit card billing cycle).
  • revol.util: The borrower's revolving line utilization rate (the amount of the credit line used relative to total credit available).
  • inq.last.6mths: The borrower's number of inquiries by creditors in the last 6 months.
  • delinq.2yrs: The number of times the borrower had been 30+ days past due on a payment in the past 2 years.
  • pub.rec: The borrower's number of derogatory public records (bankruptcy filings, tax liens, or judgments).

Several columns don't have have a good range/ variance, meaning they may not be ideal features for machine learning models. Eg: nq.last.6mths, delinq.2yrs, pub.rec

Paid Loan Status¶

Comparing the Loan default frequency for various different variables can help determine which variable may be usefu to predict a default. Based on this analysis, we can determine that the following variables are not useful because they don't differ for the 2 groups of not.fully.paid:

  • installment
  • log.annual.inc
  • dti
  • days.with.cr.line
  • revol.bal
  • delinq.2yrs
In [177]:
selected_columns = list(df.columns)

selected_columns = [x for x in selected_columns if x not in {"not.fully.paid", "delinq2yrs", "pub.rec"}]

for col in selected_columns:
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 4))
    sns.histplot(
        data=df,
        x=col,
        hue="not.fully.paid",
        bins=30,
        element="bars",

        alpha=0.7,

    plt.tight_layout()

Debt to Income Ratio (DTI)¶

Three is a significant difference in DTI between different FICO score groups. DTI ratios get significantly better as their credit rating score increases, i.e they get more right skewed.

# Test if  means are  actually different 
groups = [df[df['fico.score.labels'] == label]['dti'].dropna()
          for label in df['dti'].unique()
          if label != "Poor"]  # skip Poor if no data

f_stat, p_value = f_oneway(*groups)

# Reject Null! Statistically different means for different FICO scores
print("ANOVA F-statistic:", f_stat)
print("p-value:", p_value)

tukey = pairwise_tukeyhsd(
    endog=df['dti'],
    groups=df['fico.score.labels'],
    alpha=0.05
)

print(tukey)

Interest Rate (int.rate)¶

Mean interest paid across all credit scores is ~12%. Data is slightly positivly skewed, meaning more people are paying lower interest rates than the mean. Mean and distribution of interest rates paid differ greatly across different FICO scores categories, with lower credit ratings paying more interest as expected.

Purpose of the loan (purpose)¶

We can see bar plot with the most common categories of loan purpose. Debt consolidation seems to be the most common followed all other and credit card, which account for for more than 70% of total. In the second graph with loan purpose grouped by different FICO scores, the main loan purpose differ greatly.

# Pivot to get one column per FICO bucket
purpose_by_fico = (
    df
      .groupby(['purpose','fico.score.labels'])
      .size()
      .unstack(fill_value=0)
)

# Plot every column as its own subplot
axes = purpose_by_fico.plot.bar(subplots=True, layout=(2, 2), figsize=(12, 8), legend=False, rot=90, color="#1f77b4").flatten()

# Annotate percentages on each bar
for ax, label in zip(axes, purpose_by_fico.columns):
    counts = purpose_by_fico[label]
    total = counts.sum()
    for bar in ax.patches:
        height = bar.get_height()
        pct = height / total * 100
        ax.text( bar.get_x() + bar.get_width()/2, height, f"{pct:.1f}%", ha='center', va='bottom', fontsize='8')
    ax.set_title(f"{label} FICO scores")

plt.tight_layout()
plt.savefig(fig_dir / f"bar_purpose_by_fico.png", dpi=300)
plt.show()

Feature selection¶

Columns to maintain for ML models:

  • credit.poicy: significant difference in distribution for not.fully.paid loans. Good binary variable
  • purpose: significant difference in distribution for not.fully.paid loans. Good categorical variable
  • fico: fico by itself seems to reasonable be a good predictor of default by it's highly correlated with other variables such as int.rate. It has a considerable difference in distribution for no.fully.paid loans and has a high variance.
  • revol.util: Has a considerable variance and differs significatly in distibution for not.fully.paid loans.
  • inq.last6mths: Has a considerable difference in the distribution for not.fully.paid loans by default status. However it's moderatly correlated with other possible features such as int.rate and fico and has a low variance.
In [184]:
# Maybe drop: int.rate
